Example idea: export configurable props (variant, size, disabled, as), provide distinct focus styles and ARIA support, and avoid using non-semantic elements alone. Example code (simplified):

import React from 'react';

type ButtonProps = React.ButtonHTMLAttributes<HTMLButtonElement> & { variant?: 'primary'|'ghost'; size?: 'sm'|'md'|'lg' };

export const Button: React.FC<ButtonProps> = ({ variant='primary', size='md', children, ...rest }) => (
  <button
    className={`btn btn-${variant} btn-${size}`}
    {...rest}
  >
    {children}
  </button>
);

Key points: provide a focusable outline, keyboard activation support, propagate attributes like aria-pressed/aria-expanded, and demonstrate interactions and keyboard navigation in Storybook.

Approach: 1) Use useForm to manage form state; 2) Use watch to control rendering of conditional fields based on another field's value; 3) Trigger asynchronous validation on onBlur or on submit and display friendly errors; 4) Enable stepwise saving for long forms. Simplified example:

const { register, handleSubmit, watch, setError } = useForm();
const showExtra = watch('hasExtra');

<form onSubmit={handleSubmit(onSubmit)}>
  <input {...register('email', { required: true })} />
  <input type="checkbox" {...register('hasExtra')} />
  {showExtra && <input {...register('extraField')} />}
</form>

Asynchronous validation: call the backend API in onSubmit or onBlur, and use setError to set field errors on failure. Use debounce to reduce request frequency.
